Hover.description: Hover state for text and icon elements that start at Neutral Foreground 1 for rest state

Pressed.description: Pressed state for text and icon elements that start at Neutral Foreground 1 for rest state

Selected.description: Selected state for text and icon elements that start at Neutral Foreground 1 for rest state

Hover.description: Hover state text, used in menus, list items (i.e. Chat, channels). In v9, this is usually associated w/ Neutral Foreground 2 as the rest state (hence the numbering)

Pressed.description: Pressed state text/icons (usually paired w/ a visible background color change.

Selected.description: Selected state text/icons. This needs to be paired with a Neutral Background 2 Selected token or a Transparent Background Interactive token

Hover.description: Hover state color for icon buttons (“Transparent” or “Subtle” variant) and menu list items that have icons. In both, it is paired w/ v9’s Transparent Background Interactive

Pressed.description: Pressed state color for icon buttons (“Transparent” or “Subtle” variant) and menu list items that have icons. In both, it is paired w/ v9’s Transparent Background Interactive

Selected.description: Selected state color for icon buttons (“Transparent” or “Subtle” variant) and menu list items that have icons. In both, it is paired w/ v9’s Transparent Background Interactive

Rest.description: Hover state color for icon buttons (“Transparent” or “Subtle” variant) and menu list items that have icons. In both, it is paired w/ v9’s Transparent Background Interactive
Text link color for when you want the color to stay neutral (or more subtle) and closer with the rest of the body text.

Hover.description: Hover state for text link color for when you want the color to stay neutral (or more subtle) and closer with the rest of the body text.

Pressed.description: Pressed state for text link color for when you want the color to stay neutral (or more subtle) and closer with the rest of the body text.

Rest.description: This was added to make placeholder text in input fields subtler when compared against user inputted text. Use this sparingly as the text only passes 4.5:1 contrast up until Background 3
Disabled/Inactive state for controls that the user can’t interact with. Note: In V9 we simplified the number of disabled tokens supported, make sure associated background is updated as well.

Inverted text that needs to stay white across all themes. Examples of this include confirmation/toasts where the background is dark in an other light UI (but then in dark theme we want to keep the toast bg dark)
Used for text/icon elements on inverted background surfaces. True inversion across all themes

Hover.description: Hover state for elements using NeutralForegroundInverted at rest. Text/icon elements on inverted background surfaces

Pressed.description: Pressed state for elements using NeutralForegroundInverted at rest. Text/icon elements on inverted background surfaces

Selected.description: Selected state for elements using NeutralForegroundInverted at rest. Text/icon elements on inverted background surfaces

Rest.description: Used for text/icon elements on inverted background surfaces, but need an exception to stay hcCanvasText in high contrast
Added for controls that need to communicate inactive/disabled state over elements that are media, not single color, brand color, or dark surfaces in an otherwise light ui
Rest state text for interactive links over dark backgrounds

Hover.description: Hover state text, for interactive links over dark backgrounds

Pressed.description: Pressed state text, for interactive links over dark backgrounds

Rest.description: Primary button text, stays the same color between interaction states.

Secondary button borders, generally the border to use on controls.
In a UI with a lot of linework and there’s a need to establish more hierarchy between sections, can leverage this one as the primary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke over Backgrounds 3-5

Secondary button borders, generally the border to use on controls.
In a UI with a lot of linework and there’s a need to establish more hierarchy between sections, can leverage this one as the primary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke over Backgrounds 3-5

Secondary button borders, generally the border to use on controls.

Selected.description:
Secondary button borders, generally the border to use on controls.
In a UI with a lot of linework and there’s a need to establish more hierarchy between sections, can leverage this one as the primary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke over Backgrounds 3-5

Rest.description: In a UI with a lot of linework and there’s a need to establish more hierarchy between sections, can leverage this one as the secondary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke over Backgrounds 3-5, or as the Primary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke 3 over Backgrounds 1-2
In a UI with a lot of linework and there’s a need to establish more hierarchy between sections, can leverage this one as the secondary divider in combination w/ Neutral Stroke 2 over Backgrounds 1-2

This was introduced as a subtle stroke around list items (in left rail) on the Mica material or the Mac native material. Transparency is useful over backgrounds that are not a solid color as it blends better.
For defining page sections of the UI (i.e. between entity header and canvas content, or between info panel and canvas content)
Originally added for the inverted button (per Office.com’s request in Fluent 2). This is useful for when you need divider that stays white across all themes.
This was originally introduced for the Split button where there’s a divider between main button and menu button. It’s meant for linework over brand colored surfaces or over ‘inverted’ surfaces

This was added in order to meet the 3:1 contrast requirement for controls that are completely reliant on the linework to define the boundaries of that control (i.e. Toggle off, Checkbox, Radio button)

Hover.description: Hover state for elements that start at Neutral Stroke Accessible for rest. This was added in order to meet the 3:1 contrast requirement for controls that are completely reliant on the linework to define the boundaries of that control (i.e. Toggle off, Checkbox, Radio button)

Pressed.description: Pressed state for elements that start at Neutral Stroke Accessible for rest. This was added in order to meet the 3:1 contrast requirement for controls that are completely reliant on the linework to define the boundaries of that control (i.e. Toggle off, Checkbox, Radio button)

Selected.description: Selected state for elements that start at Neutral Stroke Accessible for rest. This was added in order to meet the 3:1 contrast requirement for controls that are completely reliant on the linework to define the boundaries of that control (i.e. Toggle off, Checkbox, Radio button)

Rest.description: Added to support keyboard focus borders. This should only show up when the user invokes the control via keyboarding
Added to support keyboard focus borders. This should only show up when the user invokes the control via keyboarding
When you need a control to show a border for interactive states in high contrast but remain invisible in Light and Dark themes. (set to 1px and call for this token)
When you need a control to show a border for a disabled control in high contrast but remain invisible in Light and Dark themes. (set to 1px and call for this token)
When you need a control to show a border in high contrast but remain invisible in Light and Dark themes. (set to 1px and call for this token)
For controls that need a border and to communicate a disabled/inactive state.
For controls that need a border and to communicate a disabled/inactive state, and the control sits over a dark surface an in otherwise light UI (light theme)

This is good for text elements that need to use the brand color and are not links. Used in Unread Dividers for the text and Fluent v9 tinted badge, this set contains the Teams primary brand color for light and dark theme

This is good for pairing with Brand Background 2 to create brand tint effect elements. The text color is slightly darker than typical brand primary to meet contrast against lighter shades of the brand color. Usage ex: Pill/Tag

Hover.description: Hover state for Brand Foreground 2. This is good for pairing with Brand Background 2 Hover to create brand tint effect elements. The text color is slightly darker than typical brand primary to meet contrast against lighter shades of the brand color. Usage ex: Pill/Tag

Pressed.description: Pressed state for Brand Foreground 2. This is good for pairing with Brand Background 2 Pressed to create brand tint effect elements. The text color is slightly darker than typical brand primary to meet contrast against lighter shades of the brand color. Usage ex: Pill/Tag

Rest.description: Used for text elements that need to be brand colored on an inverted background.

Pressed.description: Pressed state for text that starts at Brand Foreground Inverted at rest. Used for text elements that need to be brand colored on an inverted background.

Rest.description: Tab underline, Radio selected, icon selected. Compound in the name generally means it is selected and has additional hover and pressed state changes to move it back to unchecked/unselected state.

Theme switch.description: Theme switch. Control logic token to enable theme switching with libraries that use conventional "Light" and "Dark" mode components. For example, you're now able to assign the new "theme-switch" variable to the theme switch component property on the images component found in the Musea illustration library.
